In this topic we are going to learn about how encapsulation works with programs

#EXAMPLE WITHOUT ENCAPSULATION

class student():
      def __init__(self):            #in this code we can access and modify the variable outside and inside of class
             self.name="aravinth"    #in this we print(a.name) in outside of class
a=student()
print(a.name)    #aravinth

#EXAMPLE WITH ENCAPSULATION
->if you use two underscore '__' before the variable, you cannot change the variable value and access(modify) the variable by outside of class (example: self.__name="aravinth")
->if you put using two underscore like this you will access the variable only inside of class you cannot access the variable outside of class
->if you want to change the variable value that's also you can do only in inside of class 

class student():
    def __init__(self):
        self.__name="aravinth"  #you cannot change the value and access(modify) the variable outside of class
    def display(self):
        print(self.__name)
a=student()
a.display()  #aravinth


#ACCESS SPECIFIERS IN PYTHON
1. Public
->you can access this variables in everywhere(outside and inside of class both)
#ex
self.name = "Titus"

2.Protected
->This also same as public can access the variables in everywhere
#ex
self._name="Titus"

3.Private
->This variable you can access only in inside of class,you cannot access and modify the variable in outside of class
#ex
self.__name="Titus"






